I haven&#39;t used the mid-fetch abort, but if it truly stops the HTTP fetch
before the body is received, the rules will not have been received.

Subsequent processing may well treat this as if it were an empty robots.txt,
in which case crawling will occur even where robots.txt should have
prevented it.

The mid-fetch abort should probably refuse to abort certain URIs, either
by recognizable pattern or &#39;prerequisite&#39; status. Until that&#39;s fixed,
I&#39;d recommend allowing &#39;text/plain&#39; downloads to proceed so that robots
rules are not inadvettently circumvented.

(Occasionally robots.txt has odd MIME types, too, but I think accepting
text/html and text/plain would handle most cases.)

- Gordon @ IA

